Assess the Nature and Severity of the Plumbing “Emergency” Before Attempting a DIY Fix. Some home problems are easy to fix. Others, not so much. If a problem is particularly severe and I am not sure how to repair it, consider using a professional home repair service right away. I acct quickly to minimize further damage. Once I’ve discovered a problem, it’s important to be timely in my response to the issue. My response should be based on my assessment of the problem. For example, if I find a slow leak in a water supply line, I place a bucket under the leak site to catch any water. This can help prevent water damage to the building. However, a larger leak might be too much to handle with a bucket. In this case, I’ll want to shut off the water supply to the leaky pipe as soon as possible. Find the isolation valve controlling water to that pipe and turn it off. Once I’ve mitigated the immediate problem, I take some time to study the issue and get specific advice.
There are times I need a set helping hands. Some plumbing fixes work best when I have a second person helping you. For example, my kitchen sink have a drain and an overflow. These connected drains reduce the efficiency of a plunger—I plunge the drain, and the air simply comes out the other drain or overflow rather than breaking up the clog. Having a family member to cap the other drain while I plunge the first helps keep the air trapped in the line so the pressure buildup can clear the clog. Also, a second pair of hands and eyes can be useful for improving safety in general. ***If a home emergency is especially difficult or dangerous to fix, seek professional help. Professionals have the training and experience to handle most plumbing emergencies while minimizing risks.***
